# Prometheus and Grafana Installation on Minikube (EC2)

This guide explains how to install Prometheus and Grafana on a Minikube Kubernetes cluster running on an AWS EC2 instance using Helm.

## Install Helm

Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes that simplifies application deployment using Helm charts.

```bash
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash
```

Verify Helm installation:

```bash
helm version
```

List configured Helm repositories:

```bash
helm repo list
```

List installed Helm releases:

```bash
helm list
```

---

## Add Prometheus Helm Repository

Add the Prometheus Community Helm repository and update the local repository cache.

```bash
helm repo add prometheus-community https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts

helm repo update
```

---

## Create Monitoring Namespace

Create a dedicated namespace for monitoring components.

```bash
kubectl create namespace monitoring
```

Verify namespace creation:

```bash
kubectl get ns
```

---

## Install Prometheus and Grafana

Install the kube-prometheus-stack Helm chart, which includes:

* Prometheus Server
* Grafana
* Alertmanager
* Node Exporter
* Kubernetes Monitoring Components

```bash
helm install prometheus prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack --namespace monitoring
```

Check the deployment status:

```bash
kubectl get pods -n monitoring
```

List only pods belonging to the Prometheus release:

```bash
kubectl --namespace monitoring get pods -l "release=prometheus"
```

Wait until all pods are in the Running state.

---

## Retrieve Grafana Admin Password

Grafana's default username is:

```text
admin
```

Retrieve the admin password from Kubernetes Secret:

```bash
kubectl --namespace monitoring get secrets prometheus-grafana -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 -d ; echo
```

---

## Expose Grafana Service

Create a NodePort service to access Grafana externally.

```bash
kubectl expose service prometheus-grafana \
--type=NodePort \
--target-port=3000 \
--name=grafana-external \
-n monitoring
```

Verify service:

```bash
kubectl get svc -n monitoring
```

---

## Expose Prometheus Service

Create a NodePort service to access Prometheus externally.

```bash
kubectl expose service prometheus-kube-prometheus-prometheus \
--type=NodePort \
--target-port=9090 \
--name=prometheus-external \
-n monitoring
```

Verify service:

```bash
kubectl get svc -n monitoring
```

---

## Port Forward Prometheus

Forward Prometheus service to port 9090 on the EC2 instance.

```bash
kubectl port-forward --address 0.0.0.0 svc/prometheus-kube-prometheus-prometheus 9090:9090 -n monitoring &
```

Access Prometheus:

```text
http://<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>:9090
```

---

## Port Forward Grafana

Forward Grafana service to port 3000 on the EC2 instance.

```bash
kubectl port-forward --address 0.0.0.0 svc/prometheus-grafana 3000:80 -n monitoring &
```

Access Grafana:

```text
http://<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>:3000
```

---

## Get Minikube Service URLs

Generate Minikube service URLs for external access.

Prometheus URL:

```bash
minikube service prometheus-external -n monitoring --url
```

Grafana URL:

```bash
minikube service grafana-external -n monitoring --url
```

---

## Verify Installation

Check all pods:

```bash
kubectl get pods -n monitoring
```

Check all services:

```bash
kubectl get svc -n monitoring
```

Check Helm release:

```bash
helm list -n monitoring
```

---

## Access Details

### Grafana

URL:

```text
http://<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>:3000
```

Username:

```text
admin
```

Password:

```bash
kubectl --namespace monitoring get secrets prometheus-grafana -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 -d ; echo
```

### Prometheus

URL:

```text
http://<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>:9090
```

---

## Cleanup

Remove Prometheus and Grafana:

```bash
helm uninstall prometheus -n monitoring
```

Delete monitoring namespace:

```bash
kubectl delete namespace monitoring
```

